8 Poll Results That Show Donald Trump Isn't Kidding
Some tried to label him a provocateur.
Others brushed it off, taking it as a joke.
And some demand a scandal.
But no matter how hard some Republicans try to shake Donald Trump's high position in the polls, they haven't (yet).
Ten of the last 11 national polls have shown Donald Trump's double-digit lead, with some starting to seriously ask what that means for the real estate mogul in terms of the chances of winning the nomination.
Of course, this is only the beginning of the election cycle.
None of this means that Trump has a chance to be nominated by the Republican Party.
Experts point out that at this time in 2011, Rick Perry was inferior to the increasingly popular Herman Kane, none of whom won even one state in the nomination process.
And there are plenty of reasons why he would fight in a general election.
But outside groups such as Jeb Bush's Super Committee on Political Engagement and the economic conservative group Growth Club recognize Trump's unrelenting power and begin to pull out their dollars to knock him over.
Here are some poll numbers that suggest that the real estate mogul isn't just an intermediate phase:
Likes ratings for Trump turned 180 degrees.
Just before Donald Trump announced his candidacy in mid-June, a Monmouth University poll found that only two in 10 Republicans had a positive view of the real estate mogul.
By mid-July, it was 40 percent.
In early August, it was 52 percent.
Right now, six out of 10 Republicans have a positive view of Donald Trump.
About three out of 10 say they have a negative opinion.
And all these indicators prevail in the initial stages.
A Quinnipiac poll in Iowa last week found that 60 percent of Republicans there have a positive view of Trump.
Two-thirds of those who voted for the GOP would suit Trump as a candidate.
In a CNN/ORC poll conducted last week, 67 percent of Republicans said they would either be "enthusiastic" or "satisfied" if Trump became a candidate.
Only two in 10 say they would be "upset" if he became a candidate.
Only Ben Carson generates about the same level of enthusiasm as Trump (43 percent say they would be "enthusiastic" versus 40 percent of those who say the same thing about Trump).
Next level of delight?
Marco Rubio, who has only 21 percent.
On the other hand, 47 percent of Republicans say they will be "dissatisfied" or "upset" if establishment favorite Jeb Bush becomes the candidate.
Most Republicans don't see Trump's temperament as a problem.
While Trump is widely criticized for his bragging and insulting, 52 percent of Republican-leaning voters across the country think the tycoon has the right temperament to be president, an ABC News/Washington Post poll on Monday showed.
The same figure appears at the nation's first closed-door meeting in Iowa, where the same 52 percent of Republicans think he's the kind of person who could be the commander-in-chief, according to Quinnipiac last week.
Still, 44 percent think he's not the kind of person who can be effective in office, and nearly six in 10 independent voters say his temperament isn't right for the White House, according to the ABC/Post.
Republican voters are getting used to this idea.
When they put on their expert hats, Republican voters think Trump is serious.
Asked who the most likely GOP winner is, four out of 10 said Trump was the favorite, according to a CNN/ORC poll last week.
That's no longer the case when four out of 10 bet on Jeb Bush in late July.
Full Disclosure: GOP voters didn't have the right magic crystal before.
At the same time in the last cycle, four out of 10 Republicans chose Rick Perry as the most likely candidate, while only 28 percent supported possible candidate Mitt Romney.
Still, it shows that plenty of GOP voters find Trump's campaign compelling.
Even if Republicans rallied around another candidate, Trump is still ahead of everyone else.
Some pundits point out that such a spread is likely to play for Trump's advantage, and at the same time those who do not support Trump are evenly distributed among those who support more than a dozen other candidates.
But a monmouth University poll in early September shows that in a hypothetical one-on-one competition between Trump and most other Republican candidates, Trump almost always gets majority support.
He is 13 points ahead of Carly Fiorina, Marco Rubio by 14 points, Walker by 15 points, Jeb Bush by 19 points and finally Rand Paul, John Cassic and Chris Christie by 33 points.
He has a draw with Ted Cruz.
The only candidate who bypasses him?
Ben Carson overtook the businessman by as many as 19 points in a hypothetical one-on-one competition.
Just over half of Donald Trump's supporters say they've changed their minds.
A new CBS/NYT poll conducted Tuesday shows that only more than half of trump-supporting voters say they are confident in their votes.
Obviously, a lot can happen and make a difference, and no one can really say that he will never change his mind.
46 percent say they leave the door open to other candidates.
Still, Trump's fiercest competition so far is with fellow outsider neurosurgeon Ben Carson, but voters who say they've changed their minds are likely to choose Trump.
Six in 10 Republicans say they agree with Trump on immigration.
Since Donald Trump called immigrants from Mexico "rapists" two months ago in his campaign speech, the topic of immigration has become the most relevant in conversations in 2016.
Some worry that Trump's posturing will turn key Hispanic voters away from the Republican Party and prevent rebranding.
But according to an ABC/Post poll conducted Monday, six in 10 Republicans say they agree with Trump on immigration.
So as long as immigration gets everyone's attention, it looks like Donald Trump will remain in the same position.
Frustration with the government is gaining momentum.
Donald Trump and Ben Carson are now counting on the support of about half of Republican voters, mainly because of their status as outsiders.
A number of 10 Republicans on Monday's new ABC/Post poll say they want a political outsider rather than someone with experience in government.
And they're also resentful of Washington.
A Des Moines Register/Bloomberg poll in Iowa conducted two weeks ago shows that three out of four Republicans in Iowa are frustrated with Republican performance in Congress, with 54 percent "dissatisfied" and 21 percent "furious."
