Jeremy Corbyn will make his debut in the session of questions to the Prime Minister
Following mr Corbyn's election, his debut in the Session of Questions to the Prime Minister is very much awaited.
The new leader of the Labour Party, Jeremy Corbyn, will soon address the Prime Minister's questions session for the first time, facing David Cameron for the first time.
Mr. Corbin will address the first of six questions in the afternoon; his speech is likely to be closely watched by the press and Labour MPs.
He called for "less theater and more facts" at a weekly demonstration speech.
He also said that he could skip some meetings, leaving them to colleagues.
The meeting will be Mr Corbyn's first parliamentary test as a leader; it will come after his appointment of a shadow cabinet and his speech at the annual Trade Unions Congress on Tuesday.
Meanwhile, the Labour leader's decision to stand silent during the performance of the national anthem at the service on Tuesday, during the celebration of the 75th anniversary of the Battle of Britain, has drawn criticism from a number of Conservative MPs and has been the subject of several editorials in newspapers.
Mr Corbyn's decision not to sing the national anthem has attracted attention
A spokesman for Mr Corbyn said he had "stood in respectful silence" and recognised the "heroism of the ROYAL AIR Force in the Battle of Britain".
However, Mr Corbyn's shadow cabinet member Owen Smith told BBC 2 Newsnight that he would advise the Labour leader to sing the national anthem "regardless of" his belief in the need to abolish the monarchy.
Nearly a dozen shadow ministers have refused to play on Mr Corbyn's team, voicing differences over economics, defence and international politics, while less than one-sixth of the parliamentary party's members have backed him as leader.
BBC political correspondent Robin Brant says political differences are also "piled up" in labour following Mr Corbyn's appointment to a position in the European Union and the government's restrictions on compensation payments.
Mr Corbyn told a trade union conference that the Labour Party had made amendments aimed at abolishing the very idea of restrictions altogether.
Hours later, Mr Smith, the shadow minister for labour and pensions, said there was "complete clarity" within the party that it had been in opposition only to the government's plans to cut the ceiling from £26,000 to £23,000.
Mr Corbyn will be the fifth Labour leader David Cameron will meet at the courier box in the last ten years since becoming leader of the Conservative Party.
