What Happens When the Federal Reserve Raises Interest Rates
There will be a rate hike, and the bull market will stumble, bond yields will rise, and the economy will fall into recession.
We know that.
What we don't know is how long it will be before the offensive, and how long it will last.
Specifically for economics, history doesn't explain much about time.
The recession came just 11 months after the first rate hike and for as long as 86 months.
The Federal Reserve's rigidity in raising rates often, though not always, determines the response of the economy and financial assets.
That's why the U.S. central bank administration is so insistent that investors should not focus on when it starts raising rates, but on how long it will take to adapt.
In fact, there are a lot of variables in the game.
In the end, however, market participants may find that all the fuss around rate hikes turns out to be exaggerated.
"The first rate hike by the Federal Reserve with the onset of the global financial crisis will inevitably be interpreted by some as a signal of the end of the 'cheap money' era," said Julian Jessop, chief international economics officer at Capital Economics, in a commentary to clients.
On the contrary, we do not expect that the gradual return of US interest rates to more normal but still low levels will be the seismic impulse that many fear.
This does not mean, however, that there will be no consequences.
Here's a look at how some areas of the economy might have reacted depending on historical trends:
As the market has seen in the past month or so, expecting rate hikes can lead to volatility for a while.
When the rate is raised, however, the consequences are usually not as dramatic.
"It doesn't look like equity earnings are slowing down 12 to 24 months after the first jump, which again likely reflects a delay in monetary policy," Deutsche Bank analysts said in a recent study of the results of the Federal Reserve's rate hikes.
More specifically, the market has more often changed dramatically over the past 35 years — about 14 percent — upward rates, remained fairly flat for 250 days after that (average growth of 2.6 percent), then, after 500 days, returned to normal with an average return of 14.4 percent over the past six cycles, according to a recent analysis by Bob Doll, chief equity strategist at Nuveen Asset Management.  published in Barron's.
Deutsche says the outcome for securities tends not to immediately become more pronounced at the rate hike stage, and stock returns begin to decline.
Recessions are a fact of economic life, but rate hikes often play into them.
In this case, the Federal Reserve is put in conditions that did not exist before and could accelerate a recession.
Basically, the gross domestic product will be almost at its lowest point in the entire existence of the increased rate.
According to Deutsche Bank, in 118 cases of rate hikes since 1950, only twice the nominal annual GDP has been below 4.5 percent.
Even though it was 3.6 percent in the second quarter of 2015, few believe it will last, despite holding up just 1.5 percent in the third quarter, according to the Atlanta Fed.
Raising rates against such an unstable economic backdrop could be risky and raises the question "whether it will be different this time," Deutsche said.
Market participants have been preparing for a Federal Reserve rate hike all year round, with their eyes riveted on the Federal Open Market Committee meeting, which ends on Thursday.
While many strategists and economists believe that the FOMC could approve a rate hike at this meeting, futures trading suggests only a 25 percent probability.
"In our study since 1950, all rate hike cycles to date have been in a supercycle of increasing financial leverage at GDP, overlapping the peaks pre-recession very quickly after the recovery begins," the report said.
By contrast, it was an extremely slow recovery from the worst recession in the chosen period.
The current cycle so far is the longest the Federal Reserve has been waiting for since the end of the last recession; the record was 35 months, a total of 74 months and has not yet ended.
Fixed income has also become volatile while the market expects rate hikes, and this scenario is somewhat similar to the one being implemented for stocks.
The fundamental difference is that for bonds the effect will come faster than for stocks when the Federal System changes its strategic course.
In the case of bonds, it appears that yields change their vector immediately after the first rate hike/decrease in the cycle occurs.
At the end of the cycle of raising rates, bond yields immediately fall," Deutsche said.
Strategists at Charles Schwab believe the rate hike will bring long-term and short-term bond yield levels closer, making the curve flatter.
High-yield bonds often behave better in this climate, though "we're still wary of yield fluctuations," Katie Jones, a fixed-income analyst at Schwab, said in a study.
Interestingly, Jones believes that markets have already adapted to the expected results of federal system policy.
"In addition to the strengthening of the dollar and the fall in inflation expectations, there are signs that the market has adjusted to the prospect of tighter monetary policy," she wrote.
Interest rates on short-term loans have risen, the yield curve is flatter, credit spreads have widened, volatility has increased – all market characteristics as federal system policies tighten.
Generally speaking, companies doing their main business in the U.S. will benefit from higher interest rates, and local products will become more attractive.
International companies with a lot of debt will be in a worse position, as a rising dollar makes their products more expensive in the global market space, and their debt more expensive - in the financial one.
"History shows that 'quality' stocks are performing above the market for three months after the initial rate hike," Goldman Sachs analysts said in a report to clients.
Companies with a stable financial condition beat companies with unstable condition in the results of each rate increase in 1994, 1999 and 2004 by an average of 5 percentage points.
Companies with high returns on capital, as well as stocks with low volatility, also performed better than low-quality stocks, by an average of 4 (percentage points) and 3 (percentage points), respectively.
Debt will be a big question.
Companies with high-interest floating-rate debt will lose the most, according to Goldman.
Beyond pure exchange trades, consumers will benefit from a rising dollar.
Savers could see returns also through higher returns, although experts differ on how quickly this will happen.
