Vangelis Meimarakis: "Europe wants to help us."
Vangelis Meimarakis has been a member of center-right governments for a number of years, which the left believes led the country to a financial crisis.
Now, having become the interim leader of the New Democracy party, he is challenging Tsipras.
A few days before the election, he met with a Euronews journalist.
euronews: Mr. Meimarakis, welcome to Euronews!
Vangelis Meimarakis: Thank you for the invitation.
euronews: Nine months ago, your party suffered a crushing defeat, losing to the Syriza coalition, but now, judging by the polls, New Democracy has caught up with it in popularity.
What has changed in that time?
Vangelis Meimarakis: Greece has changed, and so have we.
Mr. Tsipras lied a lot last January.
Nine months ago, Greece had a budget surplus and prospects for economic growth.
Now the country again has a budget deficit and a high unemployment rate.
Investors left because Mr. Tsipras chased them away.
Over the past nine months, Greeks have had the opportunity to assess the situation in which the country was in January and the false promises of Mr. Tsipras.
And now they can easily compare what was promised to what actually happened.
Daily life has become noticeably worse compared to January, when the situation was improving, and this applied to the majority of Greek citizens.
euronews: But you say that if you win the election, you will seek alliances with other parties, including Syriza.
Vangelis Meimarakis: The fact is that, as we have understood in recent years, Greece cannot move forward without understanding and cooperation.
It is no coincidence that in all other countries where rescue programs were or are still in place, political forces and all ruling parties came together to implement the program on which they had reached agreement without relinquishing their political or ideological autonomy.
That is why I firmly believe that, at this stage, only the cooperation of political forces and institutions will allow the country to move forward.
euronews: Your party voted in favour of the agreement between Mr Tsipras and the country's creditors.
If you become the new prime minister on Monday, will you abide by that agreement, or will you try to change it, at least in part?
Vangelis Meimarakis: In fact, we voted for Greece to move along the European path, because we are well aware of the disastrous consequences of the country's exit from the EU.
Now Europe is helping us by providing subsidies to our farmers for their products, we have solidarity funds, a Juncker package and assistance in the banking sector.
All of this would have been lost if there had been no treaty with Europe.
But the current austerity measures were the result of mr. Tsipras negotiating.
I know that Europe does not want to destroy us.
Europe wants to help us.
Thus, if Europe sees that the new Greek government wants to restore order during its first year in power, acts rationally and makes it clear that the country has a strong political will to implement the rescue program, then, I am sure, all the commitments made that cannot be fulfilled due to the fact that they lead to a recession can again become the subject of negotiations.  but only after a certain time.
It would be a mistake to believe that in the first year of the new agreement, we will be able to return to negotiations with our creditors, as they expect the full implementation of the agreement.
If we want to regain their trust, we must continue the privatisation, reforms and structural changes that have been agreed, while continuing to enjoy the benefits of EU funding and the great investment opportunities that we must open up for better understanding and cooperation with Europe.
Unfortunately, during the talks, the Tsipras government did not present any serious arguments on many key political issues, which we found out when discussing these issues with our European colleagues.
I can give an example related to the income of farmers.
We have explained to our European partners that this is not a fixed monthly income and therefore it cannot be fully taxed in advance.
We were told that Tsipras's ministers had never talked about it.
That is, the Greek ministers were not prepared and ill-informed, and therefore unsuccessfully negotiated and concluded an unsuccessful agreement.
euronews: "If you win the election, you will soon find yourself at the same table as Mr Juncker, Hollande, Mrs Merkel and other European leaders.
Will what you tell them be different from what your predecessor Antonis Samaras told them?
Vangelis Meimarakis: First of all, I will explain to them that until the end of 2014, we tried to implement the 2012 agreement in the best possible way, avoiding the sharp corners in it.
We have pushed forward with reforms.
Of course, we lacked the necessary determination and speed, but we acted in extraordinary circumstances.
The market fell, and there were no potential buyers willing to pay the price that suited the Greek government.
I was the speaker of the parliament at that time, I managed to agree on the opinions of the three parliamentary groups that then constituted the government majority.
And despite their serious ideological differences on key bills, we had a working parliament, and this in the presence of populists and extremists, as well as mass demonstrations taking place outside.
And we were able to bring the country into a normal situation that would have continued to improve had the process not been interrupted by the early general elections that resulted from December's presidential elections.
euronews: In recent weeks, a massive flow of refugees has been moving through the territory of Greece.
What do you think about this situation, and about the reaction of european countries to which these people aspire?
Vangelis Meimarakis: The refugee crisis is a ticking time bomb that we have to deal with after winning the election.
And the reason is that the Syriza government did not act in this situation as it should have.
In such matters, you should act proactively, because if the problem overtakes you, then only emergency measures remain.
And that's the situation we're in now.
Even the interim government that replaced Syriza did more in just seven days than Mr. Tsipras did in seven months.
I am confident that these actions of the interim government, which is provided with valuable assistance by the President of the Republic, who called for the EU summit, will make it possible to find a solution.
We need to see how many refugees will be able to leave the country, and note that refugees are not illegal immigrants.
These are the victims of the war in Syria, the victims of some extraordinary events that have happened to them.
There is a deeply humanitarian dimension to this issue, and we will stick to the position that European politicians should take in this new situation.
The corresponding decision should be taken at the EU summit, and the United Nations should also be involved.
We also need better coordination, more effective border controls and refugee reception centres.
We must also make effective use of the economic assistance we receive from the EU in order to be able to cope with this pressing problem.
euronews: Mr. Meimarakis, thank you for the interview.
Vangelis Meimarakis: Thank you.
