Does David Cameron know anything else about Lorax?
Every parent learns one thing very quickly: if your child likes a book, it won't be long before you know it almost by heart.
Apparently, unless you're David Cameron.
Answering a question from a representative of a company that organizes children's holidays about his favorite children's book, the Prime Minister chose "Lorax" - a fairy tale with an environmental bias, written by Dr. Seuss in 1971.
It was a difficult choice, Cameron wrote in a commentary posted on the Company's SuperCamps website, and continues: "This hilarious, touching, unusual story with a strong message I like to read to my children because it always reveals some image or message that we miss."
And all would be well, except for the last paragraph, in which Cameron is supposed to retell the contents of the book, but actually tells the plot of the film of the same name, shot in 2012, with new characters and details added to diversify the rather short original narrative.
"In the high-walled city of Vsenujville, where there was no greenery and even the air was sold for money, a boy named Ted hopes to win the heart of Audrey, the girl of his dreams, by fulfilling her wish to see a real tree," we read in the text a description of a love story unknown to Dr. Seuss (real name Theodore Seuss Geisel), who died in 1991.
If it doesn't seem suspicious enough, Cameron's text reads almost like a summary of the plot of the movie "Lorax" posted on the Internet Movie Database: "In the high-walled city of Vsenujville, where everything was artificial and even air was sold for money, a boy named Ted hopes to win the heart of Audrey, the girl of his dreams."
It seems unlikely that Cameron, admittedly an active parent, is so unfamiliar with the contents of a book in which an unnamed boy learns about how the greedy tree cutter and "all-nuch" knitter Nakhodkins is destroying the environment, despite the protests of Loraks (whose name is in the title of the book), a funny creature with a mustache who "speaks in the name of the trees."
Most likely, such a simple PR task was entrusted to a performer who had never read a book about Loraks to a child 20 times in a row.
A Downing Street spokeswoman said the text was allegedly obtained from Cameron's office in the constituency.
SuperCamps confirmed that the text was obtained from Cameron's headquarters, but there was no further comment.
