Experts criticize the review of electronic cigarettes from Public Health England
The government-funded agency's claims that e-cigarettes are 95% less harmful than smoking came at a meeting of 12 people, some of whom are linked to the tobacco industry, the researchers said.
Experts published in the British Medical Journal (BMJ) together with the Lancet criticized the evidence used by Public Health England (PHE) in its report on electronic cigarettes.
PHE released an important report, a "turning point," last month, calling it a "comprehensive review of the evidence."
But some researchers have questioned the reliability of the data and pointed to the connection of some experts with the tobacco industry.
An editorial in the Lancet medical journal last month criticized the "extremely shaky argument" on which PHE based its main conclusion.
In the BMJ paper, two more researchers questioned whether these claims have "solid or shaky grounds."
Martin McKee, lecturer in European health at the London School of Hygiene and Tropical Medicine, and Simon Capewell, lecturer in clinical epidemiology at the University of Liverpool, said: "A fundamental principle of health care – rules must be based on evidence of efficacy. "
According to them, the public expects PHE's claims that "the current best estimate shows that e-cigarettes are about 95% less harmful than tobacco smoking" to be based on detailed analysis of the evidence and modeling.
In fact, this is derived from a single meeting of 12 people gathered to develop a model of multi-criteria decision-making analysis in order to summarize their views on the harm associated with various nicotine-containing products; the results of the meeting are summarized in a scientific publication.
McKee and Capewell said one of the sponsors of the meeting was a company called EuroSwiss Health, whose CEO reported that he had previously received funding from British American Tobacco for independent research.
He also confirmed his BAT health certifications in a sustainability report.
One in 12 people at the meeting announced funding from an e-cigarette maker, without mentioning the funding he reportedly previously received from tobacco company Philip Morris.
No reasonable explanation for the selection of board members has been provided, but there are several prominent e-cigarette supporters among them, some of whom have also claimed funding for the industry in the publication.
It is not known whether the other participants in the meeting have experience in tobacco management.
The meeting was also attended by the head of the tobacco business at PHE.
A scientific paper published by the group "elegantly agrees" that there is a lack of "strong evidence of the harmful effects of most foods on most criteria," McKee and Capewell wrote.
However, none of these connections and limitations were addressed in the PHE report.
McKee and Capewell said PHE's claims that "there is currently no evidence that e-cigarettes are expensive, leading children or non-smokers to smoking" are premature.
Prof. Kevin Fenton, head of health and well-being at PHE, said the BMJ's statements had previously been answered.
He said: "E-cigarettes are significantly less harmful than tobacco smoking."
