"Sonogenetics" allows you to control brain cells using sound waves
The video shows how nematodes change direction of movement at the moment when they are exposed to sound pulses.
Scientists have bred worms with a genetically modified nervous system that can be controlled using the pulses of sound waves.
Tiny nematodes change direction when they are exposed to sound pulses too high for the human ear to hear.
The pulses exert their effect by activating neurons genetically modified to use membrane channels that respond to ultrasonic waves.
More on the subject: Researchers control brain activity with the help of light
Scientists said that the worms demonstrate the capabilities of a new technique called "sonogenetics", the essence of which is to use ultrasound to excite certain cells of the brain, heart and muscles, while the source of ultrasound is located outside the body.
Srikanth Chalasani, a research fellow at the Salk Institute, La Jolla, California, told the Guardian that the technique could one day replace deep brain stimulation, an invasive procedure in which electrical impulses are sent to the human brain and used in the treatment of Parkinson's disease.
Nematode worms don't usually respond to ultrasound, but Chalasani found that they began to react when they were placed in a liquid containing microscopic vesicles.
He found that the vesicles amplify ultrasonic waves, which then penetrate the worms' body.
The amplified ultrasonic waves affect structures called "TRP-4 ion channels" found in the membranes of some worm cells.
Ultrasonic waves cause these ion channels to open and excite the cells that are associated with them, according to a report in Nature Communications.
To create nematodes that can be controlled by ultrasound, Chalasani made genetic modifications of the worms so that their motor neurons used TRP-4 ion channels.
During the application of ultrasound to affect modified organisms, sound waves were amplified by microscopic vesicles and injected into the worms' bodies, activating the modified motor neurons.
This technique is similar to the one used in "optogenetics" - a new direction that allows scientists to turn neurons on and off using light pulses.
Chalasani argues that compared to this technique, sonogenetics may have some advantages.
Unlike light, which is delivered to the desired part of the brain via optical fiber, low-frequency ultrasonic waves pass unhindered through the tissues of the body, so they do not need to pass inside the skull to deliver them.
"We believe that for the treatment of certain neurological diseases in a clinical setting, the use of gene therapy and therapeutic viruses will be able to temporarily make human neurons sensitive to the ultrasound signal," Chalasani said.
He added that, in addition, the technique can be applied to muscle and insulin-producing cells.
