Eight Golden Rules for Living in Student Residences
It's been 11 years since I moved into a college dormitory as a normal 19-year-old still believing in berets and moral relativism, but it's only now that I remember the strained smiles of those I annoyed — and the many, long-running complaints about others.
Basically, what I've learned can be broken down according to eight simple rules.
Moving into a hostel can range from mildly nerve-wracking to downright intimidating.
It encourages chatter: tell people where you're from, whether you took a sabbatical and where you spent it, whether you support Corbyn and why you 'honestly, neither love nor hate Marmite, because, seriously, guys, it's just a yeast extract OF HAHAHA, I'll be at home."
Take a break.
And help others take a break too – ask questions and show interest.
It keeps the conversation going and helps you find people you like, not people you wouldn't even talk to, even if your eyelashes caught fire and they handed out fire extinguishers.
Give people space.
People's rooms often turn into drinking establishments, midnight cinema halls and places of communal gatherings, but they are also a place where people dress up and adjust their underwear.
More on the subject: Do not even think to start studying at the university, being in a relationship
Introverts in universities are treated unfairly.
Your room should be a refuge, however, many hostels form a culture of staggering from one room to another, which promotes friendship, communication and leads to long friendships.
It can be hell for someone who is trying to recuperate.
Nothing in the culture allows you to say, "I like you and I want to continue to be friends with you, but I need you to leave and I can regain the energy I spent communicating with you."
Try to feel when a fellow student is tired of communication - and not knock on his door, but send an SMS.
Speaking of knocking: do it.
One guy in my dorm followed this principle: if the door was not locked, he was invited to enter.
He saw something.
Make friends with baked goods.
Since you start your university life at the peak of the Popularity of the Bake-Off show, knocking on people's door to introduce themselves and present a plate of chocolate chip cookies is no longer such a strange action, not so reminiscent of the 1950s with their "Welcome, we are neighbors, I baked you something, and now smile, and I will ask you personal questions."
Offering homemade treats is a great way to make friends.
Your neighbors will feel obligated to chat with you, and in the end, probably, your face will be associated with them with a pleasant surprise.
Of course, it depends on how good a baker you are.
Poorly molded lumps of flour, sugar, and fat are more likely to make people pretend to be asleep when you knock on their door.
Stealing food is a typical crime in student dormitories.
Of course, appropriating someone's chicken is theft, but is it theft to take some milk for tea?
Get over it with the milk owner.
Most likely, he will offer you not to be shy, even if the inside is boiling with rage.
If someone steals your stuff, it's annoying, and I sympathize with you — but try to treat it more maturely than my neighbor, who poured dishwashing liquid into her milk to take revenge on those who took it without asking.
She's in jail now.
You shouldn't make noise that will prevent people from sleeping or learning.
Not only to be a decent person, but also because you are the very people from the saying about glass houses.
The girl in my hallway asked the neighbor to reduce the sound of the drum and bass guitar, since it was 3 o'clock in the morning, and she had an exam in the morning.
In response, the neighbor turned up the volume.
When he finally fell silent at 5 a.m., she graciously allowed him to sleep for two hours, and then cut her music and locked the door behind her, going to a three-hour exam.
Wouldn't it be romantic if your future spouse settled in the same dormitory as you?
On the contrary, wouldn't it be extremely awkward, to the point of elbow biting, if you mistook a neighbor for your future spouse, got carried away with him, broke off the relationship and had to see him every day, and perhaps watch him pull all your mutual friends to his side?
Of course, you can't command your heart - but if the hot neighbor is definitely not your future spouse, try to cool your own ardor a little.
In that exhilarating moment when you realize that someone has left the keys inside their own locked room, the line between prank and bullying is thinner than it seems.
A good prank is fun, but it turns into its opposite in a matter of seconds.
Teach a valuable and interesting safety lesson by hiding something – but never stain someone's room with toothpaste and shampoo.
Lock someone else's door and put the keys in a glass of water, which you will then put in the freezer - but do not glue other people's things with Blu-Tack glue to the ceiling more than twice.
