Imported yachts will be exempt from customs duties.
The Ministry of Economic Development intends to temporarily exempt imported yachts and other floating facilities for recreation and sports from paying customs duties and taxes.
Relevant changes to the list of preferential goods for temporary duty-free import were prepared by the Ministry on behalf of the Government of the Russian Federation.
This was reported to "Izvestia" by the Assistant minister of economic development Elena Lashkina.
In June 2015, The Prime Minister of the Russian Federation Dmitry Medvedev, following a trip to the Crimea, instructed a number of departments - the Ministry of Economic Development, the Ministry of Transport of the Russian Federation, the Ministry of Culture, the Ministry of Foreign Affairs, the Ministry of Emergency Situations, the Federal Customs Service, the Federal Agency for Tourism - to prepare proposals for creating favorable conditions for yachting in the coastal zones of the country.
In turn, experts note that the main problem is the complete lack of infrastructure for storage, maintenance and maintenance of yachts.
Owners prefer to keep their ships abroad - about € 200 million annually go to the treasury of European countries for the maintenance, repair and maintenance of yachts.
The Ministry of Economic Development of the Russian Federation has prepared a draft decision of the Council of the Eurasian Economic Commission "On Amendments to the List of Goods Temporarily Imported with Full Conditional Exemption from Payment of Customs Duties and Taxes", providing for the provision of full conditional exemption from payment of customs duties, taxes in respect of imported yachts and other floating facilities for recreation and sports.
According to the ministry, this will certainly contribute to the creation of favorable conditions for the development of yachting in the coastal zones of the country," Lashkina said.
This issue was submitted to the subcommittee on customs and tariff, non-tariff regulation, protective measures in foreign trade of the Government Commission for Economic Development and Integration, which met in September, and following the discussion was also approved by the departments.
As the representative of the Ministry of Economic Development noted, the proposed measure for full conditional release when importing is essentially a benefit.
Therefore, after approving the minutes of the meeting of the subcommittee in the government of the Russian Federation, the Ministry of Economic Development will submit a proposal to the Eurasian Economic Commission for discussion with the EAEU member states, Lashkina explained.
The list of imported goods, which are completely exempt from customs duties, taxes, includes goods necessary to promote foreign economic activity and international cooperation, for use in the field of science, culture, cinematography, sports and tourism, to provide international assistance, etc. Among them are service equipment (personal computers, typewriters), control and measuring devices, drilling equipment, stage costumes and scenery,  mobile laboratories and workshops, water skiing, racing cars, motorcycles, sports aircraft, books, newspapers, magazines, musical instruments and objects for religious rites.
The press service of the Ministry of Transport of the Russian Federation told Izvestia that they had prepared mandatory resolutions on the seaports of Kerch, Sevastopol, Yalta, Feodosia and Evpatoria, which provide for a simplified procedure for issuing the entry and exit of small,sport sailing and pleasure vessels to the seaport.
The Ministry of Transport instructed the captains of the seaports of Crimea to ensure the application of a simplified procedure for the entry of small, sports sailing and pleasure craft into the seaport and the exit of the listed vessels from the seaport.
Also, the Ministry of Transport has prepared draft orders of the Government of the Russian Federation on the approval of the boundaries of the water area of the seaports of Crimea.
In relation to Yalta and Feodosia, the orders have already been adopted, the rest are at the stage of coordination, the press service of the department noted.
According to the Ministry of Transport, state supervision, classification and examination, state registration in respect of small vessels used for non-commercial purposes should be carried out by the Republic of Crimea and Sevastopol.
The problem is that in Russia it is extremely difficult with yachting precisely because of the poorly developed infrastructure.
If you look at the south of Italy and France, there is a whole constantly developing industry, in which a large number of people are involved.
In Russia, in fact, everything stands still.
Our coast is of little interest, the only piece where you can operate yachts year-round is the Black Sea in the area of Sochi, Gelendzhik, Novorossiysk, Anapa.
But the big difficulty is that in this area there are extremely strict rules of the border service: in order to go for a walk on a yacht, you need to issue a lot of permits.
In addition, inside Russia, the yacht does not even have a place to refuel.
For two days she can go with her fuel, and then the problem arises, where to get it, - says Denis Novikov, sales director of Nordmarine.
As for places for storing yachts, in Moscow and St. Petersburg there are now special hangars for yachts up to 30 m. Also, yachts are sent for storage to Turkey, Finland, Sweden and Germany.
