Kiev broke the atomic union.
Kiev has officially formalized Ukraine's refusal to cooperate with Russia on the completion of the Khmelnitsky nuclear power plant.
The Verkhovna Rada on Wednesday on the second attempt still voted to terminate the agreement with Moscow.
Agreements on the completion of the third and fourth units were signed in 2010-2012, but it was not possible to start implementing the project.
On Wednesday, the Verkhovna Rada of Ukraine adopted a law terminating the agreement concluded in 2010-2012 with the Russian Federation on the construction of the third and fourth units at the Khmelnitsky NPP.
It was possible to pass the bill introduced by the government of the country only from the second vote, the first time it was supported by 210 deputies with the necessary minimum of 226, but then 234 members of parliament voted for the project when re-voting.
According to the original project, the Khmelnitsky NPP, founded under the USSR, was supposed to have four power units of 1 GW each with VVER-type reactors, but only two managed to be built.
Negotiations with Moscow on completion led to the conclusion of an intergovernmental agreement in 2010, in 2011-2012 the Rada adopted the relevant laws.
Since there were no funds in the budget of Ukraine, it was assumed that the blocks would have to be built on a loan from the Russian side, but the funds were never allocated.
After the coup in Kiev in February 2014 and the subsequent cooling in relations between the two countries, Kiev began to curtail relations with Moscow in the nuclear industry, announcing its refusal to cooperate on the Khmelnitsky nuclear power plant and on the project to build a nuclear fuel plant in Ukraine.
The only area where relations were preserved was the purchase of fuel for existing Ukrainian nuclear power plants in the Russian Federation (they provided about half of the country's electricity generation), since so far the Ukrainian NNEGC Energoatom has nothing to replace Russian supplies.
Plans for the completion of the Khmelnitsky nuclear power plant with another contractor in Ukraine have not yet been finally abandoned: back in 2014, Kiev announced negotiations with the Czech Skoda JS.
