At the same time, the electoral commission refused to organize a referendum for the Communists of Russia party regarding the abolition of fees for the overhaul of apartment buildings.
The city election commission officially presented the results of the elections to the City Duma of Nizhny Novgorod in the municipal constituency.
In total, 1.03 million people were included in the voter lists in Nizhny Novgorod, 746.7 thousand ballots were issued for voting in precinct commissions, and 268 thousand voters voted in the elections.
More than 11.7 thousand ballots were declared invalid, and 24 were lost.
Yesterday, 12 seats were distributed among political parties, depending on the votes they received.
According to the lists of "United Russia", six deputy seats in the city duma are due to Dmitry Svatkovsky, Dmitry Krasnov, Vasily Shupranov, Elizaveta Solonchenko, Vyacheslav Rasteryaev and Igor Nagorny.
The only mandate of the LDPR was received by the leader of the party Vladimir Zhirinovsky.
Two mandates of the CpRF are distributed between Vladimir Bulanov and State Duma deputy Alexander Tarnaev.
Three mandates of "Fair Russia" go to Alexander Razumovsky, Igor Bogdanov and Mikhail Shalyugin.
Now, within five days, these candidates must decide whether they will work as deputies in the city Duma: in case of refusal of the mandate, he passes to the next candidate on the party list.
The chairman of the city election commission, Alexander Makeyev, told the members of the commission that he was introducing duty to "send telegrams to Zhirinovsky and others" in order to abandon mandates.
When approving the protocol on the results of the elections, representatives of the Communist Party of the Russian Federation announced multiple violations.
Leonid Krasnokutsky, a member of the city election commission with the right of an advisory vote from the Communist Party of the Russian Federation, proposed not to recognize the results of voting in four districts No. 21-24, recalling that by order of the head of the administration of the Sormovsky district, the entrance to the administration building, where four district commissions were located, was closed.
Neither the deputies of the State Duma, nor the candidates themselves, nor observers could go inside for a long time, and the resonant scandal with the storming of the doors of the district administration was shown on television.
At the meetings of the district commissions, all observers and members of the commissions with the right of advisory vote had the opportunity to attend.
The head of them stopped access only when the voting ended and the precinct commissions had not yet arrived to hand over their ballots.
This was done in order to prevent various provocations.
"Then the head was corrected, and at all meetings interested persons could be present," retorted a member of the city election commission Natalia Andryushina.
The Communists objected that lyudmila Aristova, a deputy of the Regional Legislative Assembly, had been illegally detained in the blocked administration building for more than four hours, about which a statement was sent to the Investigative Committee.
The opposition also complained that a number of polling stations on election day began to seal the ballot boxes at 6-7 o'clock in the morning, posting ballot papers for early voting in them.
At the same time, no one notified the members of the commissions with the right of advisory vote and observers, so they came to the beginning of the elections at 8 am.
Communists are sure that in the morning hours before the opening of polling stations, ballots could be thrown into the ballot boxes uncontrollably.
However, the city election commission, which has already considered more than 124 complaints on various occasions, according to Alexander Makeev, did not find any violations with the stuffing of unaccounted ballots.
The members of the commission also did not support the proposal of their colleague from the "Fair Russia" Maria Popova through the regional election commission to come up with amendments to regional legislation in order to clearly establish the time of opening envelopes with early voting ballots, which then fall into the ballot box.
"As part of your own initiative, please at least contact the CEC," Alexander Makeyev advised Ms Popova.
At the end of the meeting, a member of the Communist Party of the Russian Federation, Sergei Samokhin, lashed out at the chairman with loud accusations, shouting that the election commission was ignoring dozens of complaints and covering up falsifications in the elections.
"You are not here at a rally, be careful to declare!" the chairman of the election commission was offended.
As a result, the protocol was approved almost unanimously.
By September 27, the electoral commission must approve the overall results of the elections, after which the first meeting of the Nizhny Novgorod City Duma of the sixth convocation will be scheduled within three weeks.
In addition to determining the results of the elections, the city election commission refused to register the political party "Communists of Russia" as an initiative group for holding a local referendum.
Judging by the documents, the party members were going to bring two questions to the discussion of Nizhny Novgorod residents: whether they agree that fees for the overhaul of apartment buildings should be "immediately canceled", and tariffs for housing and communal services should be "frozen until 2020".
However, Duma lawyer Irina Maslova explained that the appeal of the "Communists of Russia" contradicts the law.
FedEx's revenue is mixed, with lower projections for 2016.
FedEx reported disappointing results for the last quarter, and the delivery service giant reduced its annual profit forecast due to falling demand for trucking services and rising costs in its ground transportation division.
The company also said it plans to hire roughly 55,000 seasonal workers for the holidays.
At the same time last year, FedEx said it would hire 50,000 temporary workers for the holidays.
Its shares fell about 2.5 percent in preliminary trading 45 minutes before the exchange opened on Wednesday.
FedEx Corp. said it plans to earn between $10.40 and $10.90 in the fiscal year that ends next May, down 20 cents from a previous forecast.
Analysts had expected $10.84 according to the FactSet survey.
The downgrade comes despite an average 4.9 percent rise in rates that will take effect Jan. 4 and rising fees for land transportation of heavy or oversized cargo that begins in November.
The company said it still plans to grow revenue year-over-year thanks to lower costs, higher gross revenue and growth in online commerce.
Chairman and CEO Fred Smith said the company "performed steadily given weak, relatively than forecast, economic conditions, particularly in manufacturing and global trade."
Plans to hire labor over the holidays were announced the day after a competitor, UPS, announced that it planned to hire an additional 95,000 employees, about the same number it hired last year.
For the quarter that ended Aug. 31, FedEx earned $692 million, up 6 percent from a year earlier.
Earnings per share were $2.42, close to the forecast of an average of $2.44 per share conducted by Zacks Investment Research in a survey of 12 analysts.
Revenue increased 5% to $12.3 billion.
Six analysts polled by Zacks estimated $12.23 billion.
FedEx has suffered in recent years from a downturn in the international urgent services sector, resulting in a lack of gross revenue growth in its express shipping division.
However, the boom in online shopping has dramatically improved the results at FedEx Ground.
In the last quarter, ground transportation revenue grew by 29%, but operating income remained broadly unchanged due to increased costs for large shipments and self-insurance.
The Express Division received higher revenue due to higher basic rates, while in the freight sector revenue fell due to higher labour costs.
In preliminary trading, about an hour before the opening of the stock exchange, FedEx shares fell by $ 3.85 or 2.5 percent - to $ 150.15.
They closed Tuesday, falling 11 percent for the year and 17 percent below the Record of June 11.
In the most anticipated meeting in years, Federal Reserve officials will spend two days this week at a 27-foot Honduran mahogany table, deciding whether it's time to raise the key interest rate for the first time in nearly a decade.
At one end of the ornate meeting room, two stories high, a wall image of the United States will loom over them.
This map is a reminder that Federal Reserve Chairman Janet L. Yellen and her colleagues should put the country's economic interests above all others.
The central bank received a double instruction from Congress: to maximize employment in the United States and keep prices stable here.
But since the Great Recession, federal leaders have recognized that there is a third, unwritten mandate: financial stability.
And that third assignment may prove to be an unknown factor in the near-projected decision, which will be announced On Thursday, on whether the U.S. economy is ready to break away from the unprecedented stimulus provided by near-zero short-term interest rates since late 2008.
Even though most of the data shows strong growth, the recent turmoil in global financial markets could deter already cautious federal system leaders from adding volatility by raising the benchmark federal funds rate — even by as little as a quarter of a percentage point.
"Clearly, the labor market and inflation will be the first and most important subject of consideration," said Lindsey M. Piegza, chief economist at brokerage Stifel Nicolaus & Co.
"However, I think that if they were looking for a reason not to raise rates, the increased uncertainty around the global market is enough to give them an excuse to wait further," she said.
There is no consensus on what the Federal Reserve will do, which in itself provokes fluctuations in the financial market.
About half of the economists recently surveyed by Bloomberg predicted an increase in interest rates this week.
Financial markets, however, expect the federal system to refrain from doing so, with the key indicator showing only a roughly 30 percent chance of a rapid upswing.
This could lead to a fall in the stock market if the federal system raises the rate, provided that decision-makers do not soften the blow with the promise that the next increase will not be soon.
On Tuesday, the Dow Jones rose 228.89 points, or 1.4%, to 16,599.85.
The takeoff was triggered by expectations that those defining the federal system's strategy would drop bet this week, said John Lonsky, chief economist at Moody's Capital Markets Research.
"It will be a surprise if the federal system raises rates at this point in time," he said.
If federal reserve officials do so, "they will have to go far in approving their strategy to keep financial markets in their hands so they don't panic."
Other experts countered that a rate hike could calm financial markets as it would remove uncertainty about how the federal system would operate.
Just a month ago, the federal system seems inclined to raise rates by 0.25% this month, taking the first small step in a slow tightening of financial conditions that could confirm the strength of the U.S. recovery.
Yellen said in the spring and early summer that she expected a rate hike this year, despite complaints from liberals that more economic progress was needed.
Although the emergence of new jobs slowed in August, labor market growth has been stable this year.
Unemployment fell to 5.1% last month, the lowest in more than seven years, and nearly at what the federal system considers full-time employment.
Wage growth is showing signs of acceleration.
And, although inflation continues to be below the central bank's annual target of 2%, the leadership of the Federal System said that the key reason was the temporary effect of a sharp drop in oil prices.
The economy "can and does cope with higher rates, and needs them, given the shrinking labor market," said Ian Shepherdson, chief economist at Pantheon Macroeconomics.
However, financial markets around the world began to shake late last month, after China devalued its currency.
The Average Dow Jones Industrial Average fell as much as 16% from a record high in May as investors feared a slowdown in the Chinese economy could weigh on global growth.
The market has partially regained its position this month, and the Dow Jones index is now about 10% below the high May value.
For the leadership of the Federal Reserve System, market outrage further complicates the difficult calculations of the timing of the interest rate hike.
"In the absence of information about what has happened in the financial markets and news about the weakness of the Chinese economy in the past few weeks, they would have tightened the screws at this meeting," said Stephen D. Ohliner, senior researcher at the UCLA Ziman Center for Real Estate and a former Federal Reserve official.
Now, he predicts, they will wait at least a month to gain more control over the aftermath.
"There's a lot of uncertainty about what the implications might be for the U.S. economy, and they have almost no reliable data after the recent events in China," Ohliner said.
The health of the world economy is not a major concern of the Federal System and should not technically be taken into account in these decisions.
But essentially, the Federal Reserve has become the world's financial power.
The influence of the Central Bank in recent years has been enormous.
The mere hint from then-Chairman Ben S. Bernanke in 2013 that the Federal Reserve might "mute" its monetary expansion caused market turmoil around the world.
In a world where markets and economies are increasingly intertwined, one would expect Federal Reserve executives to not only monitor developments everywhere, but also consult with representatives of other central banks and experts to better understand the global economy.
Their decision-making process is "more of an art than a science," said Zachary Karabell, chief executive at Envestnet Inc, a company that focuses on global wealth management strategies.
Jeffrey Laqueur, president of the Federal Reserve Bank of Richmond, Virginia, noted this month that "there have been instances in the history of the Federal Reserve system of overreactions to financial market movements that do not seem to be related to economic principles."
Laqueur, a voting member of the powerful Federal Open Market Committee who pushed for a rate hike, cited the 1998-99 decisions as an example.
The Asian financial crisis has caused the Federal System to cut its benchmark rate by 0.75% in three meetings, "despite limited identifiable implications for U.S. growth," Laqueur said.
A year later, federal system officials reversed those cuts.
The Federal Reserve should prioritize concerns about stability only in times of big crises, such as the market crash in 2008," said Adam S. Posen, a former member of the interest rate committee at the Bank of England.
The latest panic has come nowhere near that level, he said.
"You certainly wouldn't want to be in a situation where you're scared of rising rates because markets are going through a shock," said Posen, president of the Peterson Institute for Global Economics.
The Federal Reserve Act still has a dual mandate and doesn't mention financial stability, and until that changes, I don't think they should get ahead of the curve.
