Diabetics with mild obesity may be helped by obesity surgery
The beneficial effect after obesity surgery in people with mild obesity with type 2 diabetes can last at least five years, according to a new study.
However, it is too early to say that low-obese diabetics live longer after obesity surgery than those who receive nonsurgical treatment.
"Mortality statistics don't show up right away," said Dr. Robin Blackstone, an expert in obesity surgery who wrote about the new study in a column by the editor of JAMA Surgery.
Obesity surgery, or bariatric surgery, uses a variety of techniques to reduce the size of the stomach.
They reduce hunger and limit the ability of organis to absorb food.
Over the years, bariatric surgery has proven effective for treating type 2 diabetes, but major studies have been conducted among people with morbid obesity who have a body mass index (BMI) of 35 or higher.
BMI, a measure of weight relative to height, is considered normal at a value between 18.5 and 24.9.
A BMI of 25 or higher indicates that a person is overweight, and people with a BMI above 30 are considered obese.
You can calculate your BMI here: 1.usa.gov/1D0ZqDv.
For the new study, researchers at Taiwan's Min-Sheng General Hospital used data collected from 2007 to compare two types of bariatric surgery — gastric bypass surgery and sleeve gastrectomy — with medical treatment for type 2 diabetes in people with mild obesity.
The average BMI of those who underwent surgery fell from 31 to 24.5 by the end of the fifth year of their participation in the study.
At the same time, the BMI of those who have received nonsurgical treatment for diabetes remains at about 29.
Among those who underwent surgery, 36% were completely cured of diabetes, and 28% were partially cured.
In the group receiving medical treatment, for comparison, a complete cure for diabetes was observed in only 1%, and partial - only in about 2%.
In addition, blood pressure, triglycerides, and "bad" LDL cholesterol "were generally better in the surgical group," the authors state.
The researchers also monitored hemoglobin A1c levels in the blood, which reflect blood sugar levels in dynamics.
Hemoglobin A1c is best kept below 7%, the researchers wrote.
After surgery, the average hemoglobin A1c level decreased from about 9% to about 6%.
In the therapeutic group, however, it remained stable, at about 8%.
But better glycemic control scores, reflected by good hemoglobin A1c levels, did not reduce the mortality rate over five years, according to study leader Dr Chi-Cheng Soo and colleagues.
The research team also compared the average outcomes of the two types of surgical treatment.
In the fifth year, compared with the group that had a sleeve gastrectomy, the bypass group lost more weight (18.7 kg vs. 14.2 kg), achieved a greater reduction in BMI (by 7.4 vs. 5.1) and hemoglobin A1c (3.1% vs. 2.1%), and was closer to complete remission of diabetes (46.9% vs. 16.7%).
Although the new study does not demonstrate the benefits of the surgical method in terms of life expectancy after five years, there is evidence from a study of overweight people in Sweden that surgical treatment does lead to an increase in life expectancy, as reported by Blackstone from the College of Medicine in Phoenix, University of Arizona.
According to a Swedish study for obese people who chose bariatric intervention, the likelihood of dying over 15 years was about 29% lower compared to the group that used more traditional methods.
Although the new study did not show an increase in life expectancy, Blackstone noted that it encourages people with a BMI below 35 interested in such a procedure.
"Here, the report is very important because it argues that such surgery is safe in the low BMI group, where there is no increased risk of mortality or kidney disease," she said.
Blackstone added that people and their doctors should start taking weight seriously once a patient's BMI falls between 27 and 30.
"I think we're waiting too long to get people to take this seriously," she said.
It seems to me that once they accumulate the genetic changes that trigger obesity and diabetes in their bodies, it is very difficult to reverse this.
