The World Cup forced the authorities to pay attention to the condition of Russian hotels.
According to the law written specifically for the championship, each hotel in St. Petersburg must undergo a classification procedure and prove that it corresponds to the declared number of stars and the level of service.
It is already clear that not everyone will be able to do this: hoteliers are so afraid of inspections that they often do not even send documents to the requests of the Federal Antimonopoly Service for St. Petersburg.
According to the head of the UFAS Vadim Vladimirov, the department studied 138 hotels and now plans to open 34 cases against hotels, many of which simply did not respond to the anti-monopoly activists.
There are signs that the management of three dozen companies deceived citizens by placing one or another number of stars in advertising, Vladimirov said.
The problem is that now literally every number counts, none can be lost before 2018.
Officials suspect that during the football championship, fans will occupy all St. Petersburg hotels.
Now in the city tourists can count on 30.5 thousand rooms.
According to Smolny, in St. Petersburg there are 17 five-star hotels, 51 four-star hotels, 100 - two- and three-star, 550 - one-star.
