Fourfold increase in the number of children who swallow hand sanitizer in the last 4 years
Poison control centers in the United States have reported a nearly 400 percent increase since 2010 in the number of children under the age of 12 who have ingested a high-alcohol hand sanitizer, according to the Georgia Poison Control Center.
According to Dr. Gaylord Lopez, director of the Georgia Poison Control Center, cases of children under the age of 12 ingesting hand sanitizers reported to poison control centers increased from 3266 in 2010 to 16117 in 2014.
"Children come into contact with these substances more often, and unfortunately, some percentage of them are sent to the emergency room," Lopez told CNN.
He said some children drink the disinfectant liquid on purpose, and some do it to impress their friends, or to argue for social media.
Videos on Youtube show teenagers drinking a disinfectant liquid as cheap booze.
The teens reportedly mixed a disinfectant liquid with an alcohol-containing mouthwash to get a stronger drink.
Younger children may be attracted to the pleasant smells of disinfectant liquid.
"The child doesn't think it could hurt him," Lopez said.
Many of the most attractive (hand sanitizing liquids) are those that are flavored.
There are disinfectant hand liquids with the smell of strawberries, grapes, orange, which are very attractive for children.
Hand sanitizer contains anywhere from 45 to 95 percent alcohol.
In young children, in particular, just a few sprays can cause alcohol poisoning.
"It's a high-concentration alcohol," Dr. Stephen Thornton, chief medical officer at the Poison Control Center at Kansas University Hospital, told Fox 4 in Kansas City.
You wouldn't just leave a glass of whiskey, but people keep these hand sanitizers in plain sight, and if kids get to them, it's a quick way to consume large amounts of alcohol.
Naija Russell, a six-year-old girl who recently swallowed a strawberry-scented hand sanitizer at school in the amount of about four sprays, was sent to the emergency room for treatment.
Her blood alcohol level was 179, twice that of an adult who is legally considered intoxicated, according to Dr. Chris Ritchie, an emergency room doctor who treated her at Gwinnett Medical Center near Atlanta.
Naija confused the words and could not walk when she was taken to the emergency room.
Doctors observed her throughout the night in a separate children's clinic to avoid missing any signs of brain injury, as the girl fell and hit her head due to alcohol, Ritchie said.
"It was very scary," Ortoria Scott, Naigi's mother, told CNN.
It could very well have been deadly for my child.
Lopez recommended that parents and teachers use non-alcohol substances or disinfectant wipes, in addition to removing hand sanitizers from children's reach.
In addition to alcohol poisoning, some disinfectant liquids have been linked to deaths.
In 2013, two women from Ontario died after swallowing a disinfectant containing a toxic undeclared ingredient.
Health officials suspect the product contained methanol, a deadly agent rather than ethyl alcohol, which was listed as active.
In January, three fourth-graders in upstate New York conspired to poison their "nasty" teacher by "spreading antibacterial substances in the classroom," according to a police report.
The teacher was severely allergic to hand sanitizers and forbade keeping them in her classroom.
Police believe the failed plan was "empty talk" and are addressing discipline issues to the school district.
