Vesti Ekonomika ― Nobel Laureate: Globalization
The processes of globalization were supposed to help reduce inequality in the world.
In fact, the situation looks different, the difference in incomes of the population in developing economies, on the contrary, is growing.
Eric Maskin.
To correct this, it is necessary to increase the level of education of low-skilled workers, says Eric Maskin, Chief Researcher at the HSE International Laboratory for Analysis and Decision Selection, winner of the Nobel Prize in Economics in 2007.
In the last twenty years, the world has experienced unprecedented growth in global markets.
Trade borders between countries became increasingly open.
Proponents of globalization predicted great benefits for emerging economies.
"And these forecasts have largely come true," Maskin emphasizes.
For example, China and India received a serious increase in GDP per capita.
However, not everything is so rosy.
Globalization was expected to narrow the gap between the "haves" and "have-nots" in poor countries, which manifests itself in large inequalities in income, or rather wages.
But in fact, this inequality has only increased, notes Eric Maskin in her article "Why Global Markets Have Not Reduced Inequality in Developing Economies", published in The World Bank Economic Review, which was translated and quoted by the HSE.
Together with the economist, Professor of Harvard University Michael Kremer, Eric Maskin developed an alternative theory that demonstrates why the income gap in poor countries increases with the growth of globalization.
In the new global market, specific processes are taking place.
To demonstrate them, Maskin distinguishes four levels of qualification of specialists - A and B for rich countries, C and D - for poor countries.
After globalization, specialist D from poor countries lacks the level of qualification to cooperate with specialists A and B from rich countries.
And if the wages of level C workers from poor countries grow due to cooperation with employees B from the rich, then workers D do not feel growth or their salaries fall altogether.
The bottom line is that the internationalization of production will contribute to a widening of the wage gap between the two categories of professionals in poor countries and, consequently, to an increase in inequality.
Kremer and E. Maskin proposed a surprisingly beautiful model, an alternative to the Ricardian theory of comparative advantage.
It helps to explain why globalization has led to inequality in incomes," says Fuad Aleskerov, Ordinary Professor, Head of the International Laboratory for Analysis and Decision Selection, Head of the Department of Mathematics at the Higher School of Economics.
And like any powerful theory, I'm sure it will lead to a surge of empirical work in this area.
The solution to the problem, according to Eric Maskin, is to increase the level of education of low-skilled workers.
However, the workers themselves, as the scientist notes, do not have the means to do this, and it is unprofitable for companies to pay for their training.
In such a situation, governments, international agencies, NGOs and private foundations can play a significant role, Maskin believes.
The scientist notes that the developed theory in no way calls for stopping the process of globalization, which has brought and is bearing fruit in the form of GDP growth in countries.
Derbent: a living connection of times.
Derbent - one of the most ancient cities in Russia - celebrates its 2000th anniversary in September.
The program of festive events includes a festival of national cultures of the peoples of Dagestan and a fair in the style of past times, an exhibition of Derbent carpets and the Day of Open Churches, a historical and musical show "2000 years in two hours" and excursions to the reconstructed museum of Peter the Great.
Medieval stones of the Naryn-Kala fortress, ancient Arabic inscriptions on the walls, narrow streets and palace gardens - all this seems to have come down from the pages of "One Thousand and One Nights".
Derbent is the only city in Russia that has survived in its place from ancient times.
Although it was claimed by the Roman Empire, Byzantium, the Khazar Khaganate and the Golden Horde.
The age of the eastern plane trees, which grow in the courtyard of the Derbent Juma Mosque, is equal to several centuries.
These powerful plants are under the protection of the All-Russian program "Trees - monuments of wildlife".
The shade of the sprawling crowns saves pilgrims and tourists during the summer heat.
A visitor to the mosque will be poured with fragrant tea and treated with Dagestani delicacies - honey figs, persimmons, medlar, chudu cakes, ayran and sweets.
In Derbent, from time immemorial, large samovars have been used to drink tea to numerous guests at a time.
An inscription above the entrance to the Juma Mosque says that the building was built in 115 AH.
That is, in 733 according to the Gregorian calendar.
This is the oldest mosque in Russia.
The interior impresses with its scope and solemnity: the arcades of the domes and vaults rest on square columns and are illuminated by the rays of the sun from tiny windows.
Keeping and breeding pigeons is a traditional hobby of the inhabitants of Derbent.
Poultry owners put dovecotes in yards, under trees, in attics.
A breathtaking sight is the soaring into the sky of flocks of white pigeons, similar to the flashes of festive fireworks.
In order to defend against the enemy, the ancient Persians blocked the Caspian Gate with a double stone wall.
Going 500 meters into the sea, this structure locked the harbor of Derbent.
In 2003, the fortress walls of Derbent were included in the UNESCO World Heritage List as the best preserved monument of ancient Persian fortification architecture.
Carpets in Derbent were woven in the V century, and to this day the technology of this unique craft has survived almost unchanged.
On one of the streets adjacent to the city market, carpets are sold for every taste - palas made of wool, cotton or felt of all colors and shades, with or without a pile, with a complex ornament and a bizarre border.
The development of the city began with magals - quarters with one-story stone buildings.
Over the years, the magals have not changed much.
Only satellite dishes, air conditioning on the walls and street lights remind you that you are not in a medieval, but in a modern city.
In the old part of the city, details of the water pipeline built by the Persians about a thousand years ago have been preserved.
Ancient springs have survived to this day, in which local residents still collect water today.
Many Derbent residents prefer water from the taps to water from proven historical fountains.
In Derbent there was one of the centers of pottery.
Irrigated and painted vases, dishes, jugs, cups were valued throughout the Caucasus.
The hands of potters still make wonderful ceramic products for both practical and souvenir purposes.
On the days of holidays and festivals, crowds of spectators gather under a tightrope, on which students of the Republican School of Circus Art perform.
The history of amazing and risky craftsmanship dates back several centuries.
A new trend - among tightrope walkers you can increasingly see girls.
In the premises of the former Maiden Bath today there is a museum "Culture and Life of Ancient Derbent".
Previously, unmarried girls and brides accompanied by friends bathed here, and now anyone can see the vaulted-domed hall, hot and cold pools, past bathing accessories.
Most houses in Derbent have hot water, but baths and steam rooms are as popular these days as they were in the old days.
The benefits of warming up the body with steam are written in old books.
After the bath, the blood improves, the muscles lose fatigue, the body acquires flexibility and lightness.
The festival "Commonwealth", which takes place on the territory of the Naryn-Kala fortress, is attended by ethnic compounds of many districts of Dagestan.
Participants in national costumes dance, play folk melodies, perform songs of the peoples of the Caucasus and treat visitors to delicious homemade cheese.
Kırkhlar is the burial place of forty martyrs who laid down their heads for Islam.
This is one of the most revered complexes for Muslims of the North Caucasus.
Yellowed by time, the sarcophagi are carved from solid stone blocks and are oriented, as is customary among the Arabs, along the west-east axis.
Brothers Gavril and Albert Yakubov cut and shave customers in a small salon near the Upper Bazaar.
A hairdresser on this site has been located for many years.
The techniques of the barber's craft are passed down from generation to generation.
At the same time, the Yakubov brothers can make not only a traditional, but also the most modern hairstyle.
On one of the streets of the Old Town, the house in which the Decembrist writer Alexander Bestuzhev-Marlinsky, exiled to the Caucasus, lived, has been preserved.
Having learned the Turkic language and collected ethnographic material, he described Derbent in the first third of the XIX century with its ancient monuments, life and way of life of the townspeople.
Teahouse is a traditional club of the East, where only tea and homemade cakes are served.
Men come here to quench their thirst, chat with friends and solve some work problems.
As in past times, women are not recommended to cross the threshold of the teahouse.
The Derbent dance ensemble "Caspiy" was created three years ago, but has already managed to take part in the events of the republican and Russian levels.
Soloists of the ensemble rehearse every day, learning to perfection the folk Avar, Dargin, Tat, Armenian dances.
With the onset of the evening, when the noise subsides and street lamps are lit, local residents sit on benches near houses with protruding terraces.
As a rule, Derbent residents discuss everyday issues.
But on the eve of the anniversary, they increasingly recall episodes of the unique history of their city, which influenced the fate of the entire Black Sea-Caspian region.
