The U.S. Embassy regrets the closure of the American Center in Moscow.
The U.S. Embassy in Russia expressed regret over the closure of the U.S. Center for Foreign Literature at the Library of Foreign Literature.
The center has been working in Moscow for more than 22 years.
The U.S. Embassy in Moscow deeply regrets the Russian government's unilateral decision to close the U.S. Embassy Center at the Rudomino All-Russian State Library in Moscow.
"The unilateral steps taken by the Russian Federation recently call into question the commitment of the Russian government to ties between the Russian and American peoples, which were not interrupted even during the Cold War and at other difficult moments in the long history of relations between our countries," US Ambassador John Tefft said in a statement to Interfax.
The American Center created deep and strong ties between the people and culture of Russia and the United States.
It was the center of American culture, history, and literature in the Russian capital, and also served as a venue for meetings with numerous American prominent figures, among whom were astronauts, artists, athletes, scientists, politicians and writers.
"Last year alone, the American Center held more than 400 cultural and educational events and received more than 50,000 Russian visitors," the diplomat stressed.
Tefft recalled that about a year ago it was decided to close another joint Russian-American project - the FLEX (Future Leaders Exchange Program) educational exchange program.
