In two of the three cases, the court decides to stop construction leading to pollution.
The stakes are incredibly high: in the less than 60 years since the declaration of independence of enhanced industrial development, India has transformed itself from a land of virgin jungle into one of the most overpopulated and polluted countries in the world.
The problem is particularly acute in large metropolitan areas, where infrastructure development has not kept pace with rapid urbanization: cities are covered with dense smog, rivers are filled with pesticides and waste from enterprises and households, and the few remaining residential areas are cut down for construction with new residential quarters.
Despite the formal support of the green movement from the state, NRT is regularly criticized by the government of Narendra Modi, as it often becomes the main reason for the cancellation of major investment projects.
In May this year, for example, the environment minister called the court's decisions "extreme" and "unenforceable."
Sometimes court decisions are indeed impossible to enforce within the deadline set by the court, confirms environmental lawyer Raj Panjwani.
However, impossible deadlines have a positive side: at least, they make those responsible move.
"His main goal is to shake up this system," the lawyer adds.
The Green Tribunal has repeatedly canceled major construction projects: on its account the termination of the construction of an airport, a power plant and hundreds of smaller structures.
At the same time, people are also trying not to forget: for example, during a discussion of the fate of a pharmaceutical company in the state of Telagnan, which polluted the local river with fluoride.
We can close your factory, but we are also responsible for the economic consequences.
"People will lose their jobs," Kumar commented on his decision.
However, such explanations are not always understood by ordinary people, whose lives can change thanks to one stroke of a judge's pen.
Thus, in April, the Tribunal decided to ban all vehicles over 10 years of age from entering the capital, which caused popular indignation.
Despite a sharp drop in popularity and a flurry of criticism, Swatanter Kumar refused to reverse the decision.
Instead, he ordered statistics from the Delhi government on incoming and outgoing vehicles, and also made a proposal to purchase 10,000 additional buses, having previously learned from the factories whether they were able to fulfill such an order.
As sources of pollution such as landfills, fuel quality and even traffic incidents began to fall within the scope of the court's attention, popular anger began to gradually subside.
But the most painful topic of the principal judge was the program to clean up the Ganges River, announced with fanfare by Prime Minister Narendra Modi last year.
When it comes to the Ganges, a sacred river for Hindus, the judge often stops holding back his emotions and switches to shouting.
Do you know what the word "holy" means?
Someone poured water from the Ganges on the statue of God, and in it were feces, the judge is hot. -
You continue to pollute the river because you think: Ganges is Ganges, he will take away all our sins.
It's a river we worship and look at what you do with it every day.
Cleaning up the Ganges is the most ambitious and costly environmental project announced by the new government.
Currently, the number of fecal bacteria in this river exceeds the norm by more than 120 times.
Every year, between 1.5 and 3 of the 700 million Indians bathed in it die from infectious diseases.
In February, Narendra Modi even donated money from the sale of his suit, in which he met with Barack Obama, to the Ganges Rescue Fund and 455 other items from his personal collection.
Environmentalists immediately accused the prime minister of populism: the suit was bought for 700 thousand dollars, while cleaning the river requires at least eight billion.
Supporters of the Green Tribunal agree that India still has a long way to go before it can call itself a developed country, but they do not believe that the price of progress should be the environment.
"In a developing country, talking about the environment is often perceived as an impermissible luxury," said Malika Bhanot, an activist with Call of the Ganges. -
And the court is trying to find a middle ground between ecology and development."
A man poured blood on several paintings by Dali at an exhibition in Riga.
A visitor to the exhibition of the Latvian Union of Artists in Riga broke the windows in the museum and ruined the sculpture of Salvador Dali "The Appearance of an Angel".
Now the museum hosts an exhibition of works by Salvador Dali and Pablo Picasso.
A man born in 1985 entered the sculpture hall at 14:20.
He immediately behaved inappropriately: he ruined the sculpture, broke the windows.
Then he began to move around the premises and stained with blood several works of the permanent exhibition.
Among them is a portrait of Poruka by Miervaldis Polis.
According to the president of the Latvian Union of Artists Igor Dobychin, to whom Interfax refers, the shop windows were also damaged.
Police and art experts are working at the scene.
The latter determine the extent of damage and damage.
A criminal case of hooliganism was initiated against the man.
From August 4 to September 27, the Latvian Union of Artists hosts an exhibition of works by Picasso and Dali, which presents more than 200 original works by artists.
